description:
I'm gonna be honest here. To me, everything about Boulevard screamed of... well... oldness. Not necessarily in a bad way though! It's just that this restaurant attracts a more mature crowd, is decorated with aged wooden furniture, and even smells of old money. It's the kind of oldness that's actually cozy and comforting. I would compare it to sitting down in your grandfather's leather couch in front of a red brick fireplace. Imagine that you are also reading a very scholarly book and drinking a glass of Blue Label. Oh, and that you are wearing a monocle as well. Gotta have the monocle.

// Sea Scallops ($24) - 4 stars
// Chiogga Beets, Cana de Cabra & Hazelnuts ($16) - 3 stars

// Brent Wolfe "King" Quail ($39) - 3 stars
// Lamb T-Bone ($39) - 4 stars
// Kurobuta Pork Chop ($39) - 5 stars

// Dark Chocolate Caramel Mousse and Hazelnut Praline 'Tart' ($12) - 4 stars
// Butterscotch Pudding ($12) - 5 stars

************************** 594 ****************************

          Boulevard, after all these years, still remain 1 of the best restaurants in San Francisco, that I've been a fan for as long as I can remember. First this spot is located in ta beautiful historic Audiffred Building; second, it serves local farm to table ingredients, creative but original food; third, great wine list; last but not least, chef Nancy Oakes, a well-deserved deserved James Beard Foundation Award winner and no wonder this staple resto had been on Michelin list every year since it came to San Francisco.

       Some of the most memorable dishes for me and my folks:

- An amazing asparagus ravioli and morels;

- A popular and tasty glazed sweetbreads with fried oyster;

- Pork chop with fresh bacon, mustard greens, gigante beans, and chirozo-stuffed;

- Pheasant and wild mushroom ravioli is also an excellent dish here;

- 1 of my best is the peppered lamb chop, just stunning!

       Food is always so consistent here and service. This is the place we can always count on when we have visitors in town.
